Throughout its history, the shrine was patronized by powerful clans such as the Sasaki (Rokkaku) family during the {{ill|Kamakura period|de|Kamakura-Zeit|ja|鎌倉時代|zh|镰仓时代|qq=draft}}, and by {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshihisa|de|Ashikaga Yoshihisa|ja|足利義尚|zh|足利义尚|qq=draft}} in the {{ill|Muromachi period|de|Muromachi-Zeit|ja|室町時代|zh|室町时代|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/spot/detail/171/ |title=Ōno Shrine |accessdate=2023-03-30 |publisher=Biwako Visitors Bureau |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221208205908/https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/spot/detail/171/ |archive-date=2022-12-08}}</ref>

== Grounds ==
Main buildings include:
* Main Hall - Sangensha {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|de|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|zh|流造|qq=draft}}
* Heiden (offering hall)
* Worship Hall (prayer hall)
* Kannon Hall - Houses a wooden statue of the {{ill|Eleven-faced Kannon|de|Elffachköpfiger Kannon|ja|十一面観音|zh|十一面观音|qq=draft}} (city-designated cultural property)
* Important Cultural Property: Rōmon (Gate)

== Cultural Properties ==
=== Important Cultural Properties ===
* Rōmon gate (designated March 27, 1901)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/102/1432 |title=Rōmon of Ōno Shrine |access-date=2023-03-30 |publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs}}</ref>

=== City-designated Properties ===
* Three-Shrine Hall
* Wooden Eleven-faced Kannon Statue - Heian period
* Waniguchi gong - Muromachi period

== Access ==
From JR {{ill|Kusatsu Station|de|Bahnhof Kusatsu|ja|草津駅 (滋賀県)|zh|草津站|qq=draft}} by Teisan Konan Kotsu bus:
* 500m walk from "Ōno Jinja Sandō Iriguchi" stop

== Other Information ==
The shrine has attracted fans of {{ill|Arashi (group)|de|Arashi|ja|嵐 (グループ)|zh|嵐 (组合)|qq=draft}}'s leader, {{ill|Satoshi Ōno|de|Satoshi Ōno|ja|大野智|zh|大野智|qq=draft}}, due to sharing his name, leading to themed merchandise being produced.<ref>{{Cite news|title=嵐ファンの聖地 大野神社で「馬勝った守」 |newspaper=Sankei Shinbun |date=2013-12-11}}</ref>

